&#xa0;
defaultEvidence submitted by defaultNeotropicaldefault Primate Conservationdefault, January 2014.default&#xa0;
defaultSummary: Trade in primates as pets, wherever this trade occurs, is damaging to primate welfare and to conservation efforts.  The UK should take immediate steps to stop the trade and keeping of all primates.  
default&#xa0;
defaultNeotropical
default Primate Conservation (NPC), establ
defaultished in 2007, is an NGO that works to protect primates and their habitats in some of the most biologically diverse (and threatened) regions on the planet.  We are regularly involved in the confiscation, rescue and care of primates and other wildlife from 
defaultillegal trade in South America, and are intimately familiar with the issues relevant to the keeping of primates as pets - especially the damage wreaked by the trade on the endangered primates of the region.
default&#xa0;
defaultIn our submission  we comment only on the questi
defaulton of “whether people should be allowed to keep primates as pets”.  Other organisations are better placed to answer the other questions.    
default&#xa0;
defaultIn short, the UK should act swiftly to ban the trade and keeping of pet primates in order to prevent the inevitabl
defaulte suffering that the pet trade causes for all primates and the negative impact that the trade has on wild populations. Support for a ban has been expressed by numerous professional veterinary, research, conservation, animal rights and welfare groups
default.
default(1–6)
default&#xa0;
defaultFew primate owners 
defaultdeliberately or 
defaultknowingly harm their pets
default.
default  But by its very nature, the keeping of primates as pets is damaging and should not be allowed to continue.  
defaultIn a review of the pertinent literature utilizing 
defaultSchuppli
default and Frasier's “framework 
defaultfor assessing the suitability of different species as pets”,(7)  
defaultSoulsbury
default et.al. concluded: 
default“strong evidence supports the argument that primates are not suitable pets; it is unlikely that the welfare of pet primates can be adequately addressed in normal h
defaultouseholds”.(8)  
default&#xa0;
defaultResearch specifically perta
defaultining to 
defaultpet
default primates is scarce, but primates constitute the most extensively studied of all animal orders.(3)  Maternal deprivation and isolation from 
defaultconspecifics
default, both of which are common practice in the prim
defaultate pet trade, have been intensively studied since the 1950s and it is clear that these practices are detrimental to the welfare of primates as measured by parameters such as: 
defaultneophobia
default; plasma 
defaultcortisol
default levels; abnormal behaviours; 
defaultanaclitic
default depression/wit
defaulthdrawal; cell-mediated immunity; and survivorship
default.
default(9–15)
default  Studies of captive primates in non-domestic environments, such as zoos and laboratories, demonstrate that even with specialist care, abnormal behaviours and captivity-related complications are hard to avoid.
default(16–19)
default   
default&#xa0;
defaultIn a study of ex-laboratory chimpan
defaultzees at a North A
defaultmerican sanctuary, 
defaultchimps showed clear signs of what would be termed Post-Traumatic Stress Disorder [PTSD] in humans, according to the criteria set out in the DSM-IV (
defaultDiagnostic and Statistical Manual of Mental Disorders
default).(20,21)  A simila
defaultr study found that ex-pet capuchin monkeys resident at Wild Futures' Monkey Sanctuary in the UK showed symptoms of disorders homologous to PTSD, Major Depression and Generalized Anxiety Disorder, at significantly higher rates than zoo capuchins.(22)  
defaultPet m
defaultonkeys are highly susceptible to metabolic bone disease, diabetes, obesity, emaciation, poor fur/skin condition, and other physical ailments.  
default&#xa0;
defaultWith the great popularity of internet-based social networks and cable television channels in rural South Americ
defaulta, people are increasingly exposed to European and North American cultural practices  and are strongly influenced by them.  When South Americans see that the keeping of pet primates is legally accepted in places like the UK, it encourages them to buy these
default species even in the face of their own country's prohibitions on trade.  Pet primates in South America are almost always wild 
defaultcaught, causing an estimated ten deaths for each monkey that survives to become a pet. The work of conservation NGOs and the autho
defaultrities to tackle wildlife traffic is undermined and many endangered species are exposed to even greater risk of extinction.  
default&#xa0;
defaultTo keep any animal as a pet should not be considered as an automatic right – it is a privilege that must hinge on whether a perso
defaultn is able to provide, 
defaultand
default whether the animal itself is capable of experiencing, a good life as a pet.  Life as pets clearly and demonstrably damages primates.  There is no reason that the trade should be allowed to continue.    
default&#xa0;
defaultJanuary 2014
